I'm new to this whole FT business, but my advice? Implausibility doesn't matter if you are still able to make a compelling story.

FTL, for example, will probably never be discovered - and if it is it will probably too expensive for large-scale usage. And while a sci-fi empire that spread out over multiple star systems with no way of communicating would be interesting, it also forces the writer to hit a creative roof that they can only really raise by focusing on micro-worldbuilding rather than macro-worldbuilding.

by Socialist Macronesia » Mon May 24, 2021 6:51 pm

I think the primary problem with FT is the whole tech advancement standardization. In a poorly made graph,



If tech advancement increases exponentially as it seems to within FT (Even if it isn't exactly exponentially, it doesn't really matter because the graph is meant to simply things so that it's easier for FT nerds to understand.), then that makes the difference between a few days of research and a few days of not-research fucking enormous. FT is problematic because you can't tell where that line's going to go. More importantly, tech levels that people assume would exist at a single time are entirely different: a single little percent difference and you end up with antimatter galaxy-enslaving death machines while your opponents are still figuring out FTL stuff. And more importantly, it becomes impossible to compare civilizations because there's a point when the exponential differences within an RP have to be balanced, so it becomes quite impossible to even try to compare different groups because they're so similar, and they should be considered equals, but the line increases so much that the "FT Shift" occurs, and things that are much, much more powerful and things that are weak, but still within the F7 Shift Curve Lane can't be compared because the advancements made are both extremely different and yet so, so similar. As another terrible graph I made shows:



You can compare a sword to a gun. You can compare a musket to an M4A1. You can compare an M4A1 to a laser rifle. But how do you compare an "antimatter cannon" and a "grey goo missile" and a "2x10^999999(infinity) watt cannon" and "god's divine power?" With a standard line of advancement, you can compare an antimatter cannon to a laser rifle. Within the FT Slipway, things get all fucky-wucky with their mathematical differences, since we really can't label any of these axes, other than "start of humanity" and "now." The differences could be smaller, larger, who the hell knows! In the FT Slipway, we lose all sense of time, direction... really, everything.

That's why you can compare, say CBG Palisade and any large-scale space empire nation; Palisade may be FT, but it's not yet fully inside the FT Slipway, and therefore can still be compared to other nations. Same with PMT: you can still compare it because it's not gotten into the power-creep areas of FFT.

So, to sum things up:

1. we're all going to die here
2. my head hurts
Currently in the process of revamping all of my lore, including my signature. It's gonna probably take a while, better make yourself comfortable.

Aureumterra III wrote::roll:

aaanyways

I’ve noticed different FT 'verses have different "rules" for FT, which I think is pretty cool. There’s Star Wars style fast paced action, or Star Trek style slow going action keeping fuel estimates and all in mind, and many things in between. FT gives you a lot of flexibility, which is partly why I personally was never good at writing FT, I feel like I kinda need constraints of realism ot give me a benchmark


Sorry to but in, but I think one of the major parts of FT writing is a cooperation between the two parties, like a give and take with the desired outcome that both sides are happy with. And you really don't need to into the hard sciences to make things enjoyable, if you wanna do WWII in space go for it (that is what I did with my FT stuff and it has been pretty fun) or some sort of super hard FT go for it. FT is such a massive umbrella there is practically something there for everyone. Guidelines are good to have but think of them more as tools instead of building blocks.

If I was you, I would experiment with a few ideas. Maybe make a doc and do bullet points of things you want to include in your FT lore or nation. Maybe one that has some constraints and the other that is completely off the wall with no constraints, then build from there until you have something you like. Well from my experience, but that could be different for you. So, take my advice with a grain of salt.

Socialist Macronesia wrote:I
If tech advancement increases exponentially as it seems to within FT (Even if it isn't exactly exponentially, it doesn't really matter because the graph is meant to simply things so that it's easier for FT nerds to understand.), then that makes the difference between a few days of research and a few days of not-research fucking enormous. And more importantly, it becomes impossible to compare civilizations because there's a point when the exponential differences within an RP have to be balanced, so it becomes quite impossible to even try to compare different groups because they're so similar, and they should be considered equals, but the line increases so much that the "FT Shift" occurs, and things that are much, much more powerful and things that are weak, but still within the F7 Shift Curve Lane can't be compared because the advancements made are both extremely different and yet so, so similar. As another terrible graph I made shows:

I'd expect the opposite. In harder FT at least physics has hard limits - an interstellar civilization that been around for thousands of years is likely to advance fairly slowly as most of the low hanging fruit has been nabbed and technology has generally been optimized within physical bounds. Qhevak's already nearing that point - their conventional tech is mostly pushing the limits of Hard SF, and further advancements mostly consist of better optimizing existing tech and exotic physics stuff that requires enormous computational resources to properly figure out and exploit.

This is already starting to become true in real life - warfare has generally changed much less between 1960 and now than it did between 1900 and 1960 - same for cars, airplanes, building construction etc. Computers are undergoing exponential advancement, but that will hit hard limits eventual, and while there's other future technologies that could offer really dramatic improvements, such as fusion, AI, molecular nanotechnology etc all of those will eventually peter out and hit hard physical limits too.

(Image)


If tech advancement increases exponentially as it seems to within FT (Even if it isn't exactly exponentially, it doesn't really matter because the graph is meant to simply things so that it's easier for FT nerds to understand.), then that makes the difference between a few days of research and a few days of not-research fucking enormous. FT is problematic because you can't tell where that line's going to go. More importantly, tech levels that people assume would exist at a single time are entirely different: a single little percent difference and you end up with antimatter galaxy-enslaving death machines while your opponents are still figuring out FTL stuff. And more importantly, it becomes impossible to compare civilizations because there's a point when the exponential differences within an RP have to be balanced, so it becomes quite impossible to even try to compare different groups because they're so similar, and they should be considered equals, but the line increases so much that the "FT Shift" occurs, and things that are much, much more powerful and things that are weak, but still within the F7 Shift Curve Lane can't be compared because the advancements made are both extremely different and yet so, so similar. As another terrible graph I made shows:

(Image)


You can compare a sword to a gun. You can compare a musket to an M4A1. You can compare an M4A1 to a laser rifle. But how do you compare an "antimatter cannon" and a "grey goo missile" and a "2x10^999999(infinity) watt cannon" and "god's divine power?" With a standard line of advancement, you can compare an antimatter cannon to a laser rifle. Within the FT Slipway, things get all fucky-wucky with their mathematical differences, since we really can't label any of these axes, other than "start of humanity" and "now." The differences could be smaller, larger, who the hell knows! In the FT Slipway, we lose all sense of time, direction... really, everything.

That's why you can compare, say CBG Palisade and any large-scale space empire nation; Palisade may be FT, but it's not yet fully inside the FT Slipway, and therefore can still be compared to other nations. Same with PMT: you can still compare it because it's not gotten into the power-creep areas of FFT.

So, to sum things up:

1. we're all going to die here
2. my head hurts

Seems like it'll be beneficial for many FT scenarios and its participants to introduce some sort of defined worldwide (galaxy-wide? multiverse-wide?) stagnation that stop things from moving into the irrational realm, since it make things far more controllable. Like what Warhammer did. It also need not be some sort of interstellar catastrophe—serious resource shortage, or even just simple tech or scientific barrier can do the trick. For example, I do think that AI advancement IRL will gradually stagnate until somekind of commercially viable breakthrough from either quantum computing or neuroscience happens. Just like how microchip advancement are failing Moore's law due to it reaching the gates of quantum physics. We can introduce scenarios where these necessary breakthroughs can be hampered—after all, civilization do cyclically moves in and out of dark ages. In fact, if we take nature as inspiration, population growth tend to take a logistic curve that flattens out eventually, so there isn't really a law that says "exponential growth (or even growth at all) is guaranteed".
